{{about|the uses of the word '''pendent''', an adjective |the related noun, often mistakenly used in its place|Pendant (disambiguation) }}
{{Refimprove|date=February 2013}}

[[File:BedfordRoyalCharter1.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Charter dated 1549, bearing a pendent seal]]
'''Pendent''' is an adjective that describes the condition of hanging, either literally, or figuratively,<ref name="isbn0-19-861271-0">{{cite book |author=Brown, Lesley |title=The New Shorter Oxford English Dictionary on Historical Principles |publisher=Clarendon |location=Oxford [Eng.] |year=1993 |pages= |isbn=0-19-861271-0 |oclc= |doi= |accessdate=}}</ref> as in undecided or incomplete. To be distinguished from the spelling "[[Pendant (disambiguation)|pendant]]" which is the [[noun]]. 

* In [[botany]] and [[anatomy]] the term applies to hanging forms of organs such as leaves, branches, limbs and the like, that otherwise might be rigid or erect.<ref>Hickey, Michael and King, Clive. The Cambridge Illustrated Glossary of Botanical Terms. Publisher: Cambridge University Press 2001. {{ISBN|978-0521794015}}</ref> 
* In [[sigillography]], a pendent [[Seal (emblem)|seal]] is one that hangs loose from its associated document by cords, ribbons, or a [[parchment]] tag or tail: it is thus distinguished from an ''applied'' seal, which is applied directly to the face of the paper or parchment on which the document is written.<ref>{{cite book| first=Elizabeth |last=New |title=Seals and Sealing Practices |publisher=[[British Records Association]] |series=Archives and the User 11 |year=2010 |location=London |ISBN=978-0-900222-15-3 |pages=19–23 }}</ref>
* In various senses, such as legal matters, [[Wiktionary:pendent|pendent]] can mean "[[Wiktionary:pending|pending]]" or conditional on future developments.<ref>Dalrymple, James. The Decisions of the Lords of Council & Session, in the most important cases debate before them with the Acts of Sederunt, Volume 2. 1687 Accessible online at [https://books.google.com/books?id=FQtBAAAAcAAJ]</ref><ref>Dalrymple, David. Decisions of the lords of council and session, from 1766 to 1791 (1826) Accessible online at [https://archive.org/details/decisionslordsc01dalrgoog]</ref>
* In [[grammar]] a [[Wiktionary:pendent|pendent]] sentence is incomplete in some formal sense, for example lacking a finite verb.<ref name="isbn0-19-861271-0"/> 

[[File:Santa Maria del Fiore.jpg|thumb|left|The dome of [[Santa Maria del Fiore]], constructed in segments. The structure is stable because each segment is supported by the others. Such segments are said to be pendent.]]
Something '''pendent''' may be viewed as any member of a support system (e.g. a section of a dome or, organically, a parent/guardian in a nuclear family).{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}} A pendent component of a structure or system requires one or more of the same as itself to be functional. For example, one playing card in a house of cards requires another against it in order to maintain stability. Likewise the segments of certain types of [[dome]] rely upon each other for support, as do the individual blocks or timber frames which make up a dome whether segmented or not. The whole dome may in turn be supported by [[pendentives]] (which in turn support each other). In the construction of arches and domes, the pendent condition commonly leads to special requirements for timber [[centring]] or similar expedients during construction: when the structure is completed it becomes self-supporting and the temporary structure can be removed.
